rk on the open road, and raises crucial questions about the role of data collection in broader systems of social control.Karen Levy takes readers inside a world few ever see, painting a bracing portrait of one of the last great American frontiers. Federal regulations now require truckers to buy and install digital monitors that capture data about their locations and behaviors. Intended to address the pervasive problem of trucker fatigue by regulating the number of hours driven each day, these devices support additional surveillance by trucking firms and other companies. Traveling from industry trade shows to law offices and truck-stop bars, Levy reveals how these invasive technologies are reconfiguring industry relationships and providing new tools for managerial and legal control—and how truckers are challenging and resisting them.Data Driven contributes to an emerging conversation about how technology affects our work, institutions, and personal lives, and helps to guide our thinking about how to protect public interests and safeguard human dignity in the digital age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aElectronic monitoring in the workplacezUnited States. 0aElectronic surveillancezUnited States. 0aSupervision of employeeszUnited States. 0aTruck driverszUnited States. 0aTruckingzUnited StatesxManagement. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Privacy & Surveillance (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Privacy & Surveillance) .2bisacsh  aAdage.  aAutomation.  aBeneficiary.  aCapitalism.  aCargo.  aCitizens band radio.  aComparative advantage.  aConsortium.  aCustomer.  aDelivery point.  aDeregulation.  aDispatcher.  aDriver Monitoring System.  aEconomics.  aEmerging technologies.  aEmployment.  aFedEx.  aFederal Motor Carrier Safety Administration.  aFeudalism.  aFinance.  aFiscal policy.  